<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP EYE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICK GOLDSTEIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AND FINALLY: Green Bay Packers quarterback Don Majkowski isn't the only 
hard-rock fan in the NFL (or even on the Packers). His teammate, Packers 
lineman Tony Mandarich, who's a pal of Guns N' Roses top-gun Axl Rose, wears an 
"Appetite for Destruction" tattoo on his arm. . . . Speaking of odd 
collaborations -- Robert Palmer has teamed up with UB40 to record a cover 
version of Bob Dylan's "I'll Be Your Baby Tonight," which will appear on 
Palmer's new "Don't Explain" album. . . . Watch for Hollywood Records to launch 
a mega-dollar marketing campaign when it releases CD versions of its Queen 
catalogue early next year, which should feature a generous assortment of bonus 
tracks (Hollywood has the rights to a dozen Queen albums originally recorded 
for Elektra Records). . . . She won't be singing the national anthem, but watch 
for a Roseanne Barr comedy album in December, also from Hollywood. . . . Clever 
to the last, Devo has a greatest-hits -- and a great-misses album -- coming 
from Warner Records. . . . And Hard 'n Heavy, the world's first heavy-metal 
video magazine, is such a hit that it's already spawned a competitor -- 
Metalhead Video magazine. Retailing at $12.98, the video-mag's second issue 
features interviews with Whitesnake's David Coverdale and Steve Vai, coverage 
of Aerosmith at Hollywood's Rock Walk of Fame and footage from a Poison 
record-release party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
