1303 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEAR GOVERNOR X: PLEASE HELP CHILDREN WHO ARE TRAPPED IN A STATE OF NEGLECT; 
</P>
<P>
CALIFORNIA: THERE'S NO NEED FOR MORE PILOT PROGRAMS FOR YOUNGSTERS, RATHER A 
NEW PILOT WITH A STRONG BUT CARING HAND AT THE HELM. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By James P. Steyer and Wendy Lazarus, James P. Steyer is president and Wendy 
Lazarus vice president for policy of Children Now, a California-based policy 
and advocacy organization. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A junior-high school girl only came to classes every other day. She and her 
mother had so little money, she told a counselor, that they had to share one 
pair of shoes. Every other day, the mother wore the shoes to look for work; on 
the other days, the daughter wore them to school. 
</P>
<P>
This young girl and the nearly eight million other children in California won't 
be voting Nov. 6. Yet they have an enormous stake in the priorities set by the 
state's next chief executive. Over the past 10 years, the quality of life for 
many California children has significantly eroded even as other states have 
been improving conditions for families. The next governor of California has a 
unique opportunity to learn from these other states and to act decisively for 
children. 
</P>
<P>
Once, California was hailed as the nation's leader on children's issues. But 
today, the comparisons are mostly negative: highest teen-pregnancy rate, 
highest rate of juveniles in custody, next-to-worst in classroom overcrowding. 
Nearly one-third of California students drop out or do not finish high school 
on time; one-fifth of its young children grow up in poverty. 
</P>
<P>
There is no great mystery about turning these trends around. Strong leadership 
combined with sound public policy can make a profound difference. We do not 
need new studies or pilot programs. We do need the leadership of a new pilot at 
the helm. While it is encouraging that children's issues are being discussed in 
the campaigns, that is only the first step. 
</P>
<P>
Since California's next generation can't vote, we are offering the new governor 
a three-part plan on the children's behalf. Coupled with other steps during the 
governor's four-year term, this plan would help millions of children and 
produce long-term reform. 
</P>
<P>
Step One: Prevention. The new governor should radically alter California's 
approach to helping children by focusing on early preventive programs, not 
costly remedies. 
</P>
<P>
Such preventive investments include preschool education, child care and early 
health and nutrition services and more effective education. These steps help 
children grow up avoiding crime, drug use and welfare dependence. 
</P>
<P>
For example, early health care for pregnant women and their children is one of 
the most effective ways to prevent health and learning problems as youngsters 
grow up. But one in every four pregnant women receives no prenatal care or 
receives it too late to be beneficial. More than half of California's young 
children are not fully immunized. One in five has no health insurance. This, 
despite the fact that $1 invested in prenatal care saves more than $3 in 
children's medical care later, and $1 invested in immunizations saves $10 
later. 
</P>
<P>
The new governor can lead our state in establishing a comprehensive children's 
health program -- one that reaches every pregnant woman with prenatal and 
delivery care and every child with needed immunizations, health check-ups and 
treatment for medical needs. This is not an impossible dream: Statewide public 
health programs that California can emulate are already operating. 
</P>
<P>
For example, Minnesota instituted a comprehensive program for uninsured 
children two years ago. Already about half the eligible children have been 
enrolled; nearly every physician and dentist will serve them. The Minnesota 
Children's Health Plan provides uninsured children up to the age of 8 with 
preventive services, most out-patient treatment, routine mental health services 
and dental and eye care. The program is financed by state funds. Parents pay an 
annual premium of $25 per child. 
</P>
<P>
Step Two: Priorities. The new governor should focus on the fundamental problems 
facing children and families, not just on cosmetic solutions. 
</P>
<P>
For example, a child's well-being depends to a great degree on the family's 
financial stability. With half of our children likely to live with just one 
parent at some point in their lives, child support payments from the absent 
father or mother are increasingly important to children's financial security. 
Yet in 1988, a bare minimum of $366 million in child support payments -- more 
than half the awards courts ordered -- went uncollected in California. In 
addition, California stands to lose millions of dollars in federal funds 
annually as penalties for this poor performance. Again, this dismal record 
exists despite the fact that every $1 invested by the state in child support 
enforcement saves roughly $3.70 in welfare costs. 
</P>
<P>
Other states are already taking bold steps to improve their collections of 
child-support money. Wisconsin, for example, has established uniform guidelines 
for determining support orders, automatically withholds child-support payments 
from the wages of the absent parent and plans to provide a state allowance for 
the child if parental income and child support are not sufficient. 
</P>
<P>
Step Three: Performance. The new governor should institute a comprehensive 
approach to children's needs. 
</P>
<P>
 Kids aren't like cars: You can't rely on spare parts and you can't "fix" them 
one piece at a time. California needs to tie together services for children in 
a way that both works for youngsters and pays off for taxpayers. One of the 
best examples of this approach is Head Start, the federally-funded preschool 
program that has a 20-year track record of success. 
</P>
<P>
Besides providing preschool education for low-income 3- and 4-year-olds, Head 
Start programs help arrange for needed health and dental care, as well as 
family services and counseling. Children who participate in Head Start perform 
better than their peers when they begin school. They are also held back less 
often, are absent less often and are healthier than their peers. 
</P>
<P>
Using this Head Start philosophy, the new governor can spearhead the effort to 
integrate services for children of all ages. This means that health, nutrition, 
parenting, mental health and other services should be coordinated and placed 
where the children are located -- in schools and neighborhood centers. 
</P>
<P>
The new governor must also look for results. Californians spend billons of 
dollars on children's services. Any successful business person responsible for 
such an investment would insist on effective accountability measures and 
incentives for improvement. California children who need these services -- and 
the taxpayers who pay for them -- deserve such an accounting. 
</P>
<P>
These recommendations would go a long way toward getting children off to the 
right start, but they do not cover all the bases. Some children will still fall 
through the cracks and need tailored programs for a second chance. The new 
governor must work closely with teachers, social workers and others to help 
these neediest children, too. 
</P>
<P>
Paying for a preventive investment in children also requires a three-step 
approach. First, ensure that current programs are cost-effective and 
successful. Get rid of waste and duplication. Second, make sure California gets 
federal funds to which it is entitled. For example, the state is now losing an 
estimated $1.5 billion in federal funds for medical and mental health services. 
Third, identify new revenues to help pay for necessary, cost-effective 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
A comprehensive investment in California's children would cost about 1% of the 
current state budget -- about $20 a year for every Californian, compared to the 
$2,000 every Californian will pay to bail out the savings-and-loan industry. 
</P>
<P>
If there were a city of California's poor and especially vulnerable children, 
it would be the second largest in the state. Only Los Angeles would be bigger. 
Those children trapped in that city of neglect are looking toward you now, 
Governor Feinstein or Governor Wilson. We hope that you will remember that 
California's children need attention and compassion. Most of all, they need 
your leadership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Children ROBRT ST. JOHN / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
