779 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLUMN RIGHT; 
</P>
<P>
BUSH STEERING ECONOMY INTO A BLACK HOLE; 
</P>
<P>
HE'S BROKEN PROMISES AGAINST HIGHER TAXES AND HIGHER RATES IN ORDER TO FUND 
HIGHER SPENDING. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PAUL CRAIG ROBERTS, Paul Craig Roberts is the William E. Simon Professor of 
Political Economy at the Center for Strategic &amp; International Studies in 
Washington. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In his pathetic pursuit of a budget deal, George Bush is pulling the economy 
and the Republican Party down with him. Any agreement that emerges will be no 
less a fraud than the agreements of the past decade, none of which reduced the 
deficit. 
</P>
<P>
The purpose of each budget agreement has always been to avoid a spending cut. 
This year's deal is no different. In the absence of a budget deal, the 
Gramm-Rudman limitations would allow Congress to spend only $10 billion to $20 
billion more in 1991 than in 1990. That's not enough for the incumbents to buy 
their reelection. Congress wants at least $130 billion more. The budget for 
fiscal 1991 that was submitted last February specified a $1.23-trillion budget. 
By Sept. 30, spending for 1991 had moved up to $1.36 trillion. 
</P>
<P>
Bush has broken solemn promises against higher taxes and higher tax rates in 
order to fund higher spending. The proof is that the deficit in 1991 will be 
larger than Ronald Reagan's biggest. 
</P>
<P>
To hide from the public the enormous jump in the deficit caused by 
election-year spending, Congress and the Administration are pretending that the 
real budget issue is over how to increase taxes on 65,303 Americans who have 
million-dollar incomes. Congress wants to raise their tax rates, and Bush wants 
to take away their deductions for mortgage interest and state and local taxes. 
</P>
<P>
To comprehend the fraud that both branches of government are perpetrating on 
the public, consider the following facts: America has about 250 million people. 
Those with million-dollar incomes comprise a tiny 6/100 of 1% of the 
population. If the IRS seized every dime of their incomes, it wouldn't come 
close to balancing the budget. In 1988, the most recent year for which IRS 
statistics are available, these 65,303 people paid $43.9 billion in income tax 
-- an average of $675,000 each. If that's not paying taxes, what is? 
</P>
<P>
Bush's plan to discriminate against the rich by cutting back their deduction 
for mortgage interest would add to the declining real estate market and worsen 
the cost to taxpayers of the S&amp;L bailout. There is a large surplus of 
upper-income housing on the market, the value of which will plummet if mortgage 
interest is not deductible. Just like the income tax itself, once the rich lose 
their mortgage interest deduction, the rest of us will follow. 
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government is currently making every economic mistake in the book. Its 
fiscal policy is focused on the deficit, ignoring the weakening economy. Its 
regulatory policies have driven down the values of assets held by S&amp;Ls, 
banks and insurance companies, thus weakening our financial institutions just 
as recession threatens. The Federal Reserve, demanding a recessionary fiscal 
policy, is keeping interest rates high as the economy weakens. The Treasury, 
following Carter-era policies, favors an ever lower dollar. 
</P>
<P>
Bush's belligerency in the Middle East more than doubled oil prices which, 
inappropriately, show up as inflation and feed into cost-of-living indexes, 
resulting in additional billions in Social Security payments and other 
cost-of-living adjusted expenditures. The Fed pretends that the higher prices 
signal monetary inflation that prevents any ease as the economy teeters on the 
edge of a black hole. 
</P>
<P>
On top of this combination of the worst policy mistakes since the Great 
Depression, Bush wants to add $35 billion a year in higher "clean air" 
regulatory costs and$35 billion a year in tax increases. 
</P>
<P>
This is a prescription for maximum economic failure, which is no doubt the 
reason the Democrats have led Bush into the trap. Handicapped by a presidential 
nominating procedure that produces the weakest possible candidate, the 
Democrats are hoping to engineer a crushing recession that the liberal media 
will blame on Reagan, Bush and "the rich." 
</P>
<P>
Nothing suits the party of big government more than a failed economy to cause 
people "to vote their pocketbooks," return a Democrat to the White House and 
unleash a new era of budget expansion to "deal with the problems of the 
economy." The question is why Bush is working so hard to elect a Democrat. 
</P>
<P>
The disastrous course of Bushonomics is further revealed by the 
Administration's approval of the appointment of Michael Dukakis' chief 
economics adviser, Larry Summers, to the $185,000-a-year chief economist job at 
the World Bank. Summers claims that Reagan impoverished the Third World by 
jacking up interest rates to finance tax cuts. In fact, interest rates fell by 
half under Reagan, but anti-Reagan propaganda is now the chief requirement for 
employment in Washington. House Democrat Beryl Anthony says Bush should change 
parties. By all appearances, he has. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Opinion 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA102890-0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 299062 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 28, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Opinion; Part M; Page 7; Column 1; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
745 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLUMN LEFT; 
</P>
<P>
FRUSTRATION ABOUNDS, SO SEIZE THE DAY; 
</P>
<P>
THE LIBERALS' UNCERTAIN TRUMPET FINALLY MUST SOUND A BLAST THAT CAN BE HEARD. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBERT KUTTNER, Robert Kuttner is a syndicated columnist. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One of the political hallmarks of economic frustration is that it can go either 
left or right. 
</P>
<P>
Today, our political compass is spinning. The public is increasingly 
disillusioned with the conservative panaceas of the 1980s. Yet liberals are 
still offering, at best, an uncertain trumpet. Public opinion mistrusts 
politics in general. 
</P>
<P>
One-time Klansman David Duke won 44% of the vote for a Louisiana U.S. Senate 
seat not because nearly half of the voters are incipient Nazis, but because the 
economy there is in chronic depression and mainstream politicians have few 
answers. He is an omen that the political center had better heed. 
</P>
<P>
In Massachusetts, where I live, economic grievances have caused a tax-revolt 
proposition to be placed on the November ballot. It would roll back tax rates 
to the point of leaving state government nearly bankrupt. And Democratic voters 
here have nominated for governor John Silber, the thinking man's David Duke. 
</P>
<P>
Just to the north, in the Canadian province of Ontario, the voters for the 
first time elected a socialist government for much the same reason: frustration 
with how established politicians were handling pocketbook issues. The socialist 
New Democratic Party program is strongly environmentalist and proposes a more 
progressive tax system, as well as expanded social services. 
</P>
<P>
Jill Marzetti, secretary of the Ontario NDP, admits that it wasn't only the NDP 
program that attracted Canadian voters. It was widespread disgust with the 
cynicism and corruption of the previous centrist government, fear of a 
softening economy and a desire to vote for the outs. 
</P>
<P>
Pocketbook grievances translate into spasms of populist protest whenever times 
are hard and the public feels incumbent politicians aren't responding. Voters 
go left or right depending on where convincing leadership arises. 
</P>
<P>
Where I live, the legitimacy of much of the political system is in tatters. The 
Boston Globe recently ran a remarkable series about corrupt judges. Many 
judges, it seems, are in the pockets of legislators who practice law on the 
side. Hire the right politically connected lawyer, and a felony can be fixed 
just like a parking ticket. 
</P>
<P>
This is happening at a time when the courts are so clogged that serious 
criminals wind up on the streets. Fear of crime has contributed to a voter 
backlash and a new vogue for tough-on-crime conservative politicians. Yet the 
last conservative governor was the very fellow who appointed many of these same 
judges -- and he was elected by the same working-class voters who are mad as 
hell about crime. 
</P>
<P>
In Washington, you will recall, a conservative Administration was elected in 
1980 by voters eager to restore budgetary balance. They didn't get exactly what 
they bargained for, either. 
</P>
<P>
With the broad discrediting of the policies of Reaganomics, this ought to be a 
moment for an effective progressive alternative. After all, north of the 
border, programs pioneered by the Canadian New Democrats are genuinely popular 
-- universal health insurance, expanded child care, tough controls on 
pollution, fair taxation, affordable housing. 
</P>
<P>
In America, polls show that voters want these things, too. However, the 
political system hasn't been able to deliver them. Unless somebody breaks 
through this deadlock, the voters will be right to grow ever more cynical. 
</P>
<P>
Taxing the rich, politically unthinkable two weeks ago, is now the consensus 
position in the budget debate. For the first time in a decade, liberals have 
set the agenda, and they seem almost stunned. It remains to be seen whether 
they will be bold enough to build on this success and offer genuinely popular 
alternatives. The polls show that voters truly want a health system more like 
the Canadian one. They want less spending on the military, effective services 
to meet the new needs of family life, and they want re-regulation of liberated 
industries that went a little haywire in the free-wheeling '80s, such as banks 
and airlines. 
</P>
<P>
At long last, the Democrats in Congress are behaving a little like an 
opposition party and less like the weaker half of a coalition government. In 
politics, moments like this don't come around that often. Today voters express 
their pocketbook frustration by staying home, voting to dismantle government or 
electing know-nothing leaders -- and then wake up even more disgusted when 
things get worse. 
</P>
<P>
If liberals don't seize this moment to stake out real alternatives, they will 
have themselves to blame. 
</P>
</TEXT>
