<HEADLINE>
<P>
RANCHO SANTIAGO DENIED BALL, VICTORY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TOM BIRSCHBACH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SANTA ANA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Riverside Community College found out Saturday night that the best way to slow 
down Rancho Santiago's Estrus Crayton was to keep the ball away from him. The 
strategy paid off in a 30-14 Mission Conference victory at the Santa Ana Bowl 
that spoiled the Dons' 75th homecoming. 
</P>
<P>
Crayton did gain 232 all-purpose yards, his season average, and set a Orange 
County all-purpose record along the way. But it wasn't enough to overcome 
Riverside 363 rushing yards, the result of fullback Samita Vaoifi, halfback 
Mark Wilson and a big offensive line. 
</P>
<P>
Vaoifi ran for 166 yards and a touchdown in 19 carries, and Wilson gained 
another 154 yards and a touchdown in 21 carries as the Tigers (5-2, 4-2) broke 
open a close game with 17 fourth-quarter points. 
</P>
<P>
Crayton scored on a 96-yard kickoff return in the second quarter and picked up 
134 rushing yards in 19 carries to pass former Orange Coast star Bart 
Recktenwald for the county all-purpose yardage record. The Dons are 4-3, 3-3 in 
the conference. 
</P>
<P>
With Rancho Santiago trailing, 16-6, in the fourth quarter, Crayton was stopped 
on a fourth and seven on the Riverside 10, and the Tigers then drove 90 yards 
for a 23-6 lead. TOM BIRSCHBACH 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA102890-0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 299463 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 28, 1990, Sunday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 22; Column 2; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
448 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FULLERTON WINS ANOTHER BARN BURNER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By STEVE KRESAL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
COSTA MESA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The past three weeks of Fullerton College football have taught fans one lesson: 
don't leave early. 
</P>
<P>
Fullerton trailed by 13 points entering the fourth quarter Saturday night, but 
rallied in the final 5 minutes 37 seconds for a 24-23 victory over Golden West 
in a Mission Conference game at Orange Coast. 
</P>
<P>
A nine-yard touchdown pass from quarterback Eric Robinson to fullback Don 
Norris with 43 seconds left tied it at 23-23. Eric Lange then drilled the extra 
point and Fullerton led, 24-23. 
</P>
<P>
Golden West got the ball at its 30 on the ensuing kickoff, but turned the ball 
over on downs and Fullerton (6-1, 5-1) ran out the final 16 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
This was the third consecutive week Fullerton has been involved in a wild 
fourth-quarter finish. Two weeks ago, Fullerton scored 22 points in the final 
5:36 to defeat El Camino, 31-24, after being behind, 24-9. 
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, Fullerton held a 29-17 lead, only to watch Saddleback score 14 
points in the final 5:21 for a 31-29 victory. 
</P>
<P>
"I getting too old for this," said Hal Sherbeck, Fullerton College coach who is 
in his 30th season. 
</P>
<P>
Fullerton's comeback started when Golden West quarterback David Brunet fumbled 
an exchange from center and the ball was recovered by defensive lineman Steve 
Griggs at the Golden West 34 with about eight minutes to play. 
</P>
<P>
Six plays later, Brian Williams scored on a one-yard run and the Golden West 
lead was cut to 23-17. Golden West then had to punt after three plays, and 
Fullerton started the winning drive at its own 31 with 4:20 left. The Hornets 
went 69 yards in nine plays including a 23-yard and a nine-yard screen pass 
from Robinson to John Mountain. 
</P>
<P>
Golden West (5-2, 4-2) won't have to go far to find what would have made the 
difference in the outcome. Kicker Wayne Duplantis, who tied the state and 
national record with five field goals last Saturday, missed a 31-yard field 
goal attempt and an extra point in the first half. Golden West also failed on a 
two-point conversion try in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
Frank Vaccaro had an 89-yard touchdown run in the second quarter and Golden 
West led, 9-0, at the half. He led all rushers with 136 yards in 15 carries. 
</P>
<P>
Fullerton rallied for 10 consecutive points early in the third quarter, but 
Brunet came back with two touchdown passes as Golden West built a 13-point 
lead. He completed a 22-yarder to Troy Walker, who made a diving catch in the 
end zone to put Golden West up, 15-10, with 2:06 left in the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
With 48 seconds left in the third quarter, Brunet hooked up with Robert Bedford 
for an 18-yard screen pass for a touchdown. Brunet completed the two-point 
conversion pass to Jake Witherspoon to give the Rustlers a 23-10 lead. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Golden West's Frank Vaccaro evades Fullerton's Shawn Donahue during his 
89-yard touchdown run. Fullerton came out on top, 24-23. ; Photo, Fullerton's 
Don Norris is about to be brought down by David McLeod. Eric Marshall (50) and 
Jeff Hodges come in for assist. DAVID MURONAKA / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
